λits
/lits/
λits is a Lisp dialect implemented in TypeScript, drawing heavy inspiration from Clojure. Most core functions have been ported to λits, ensuring a robust and familiar experience for Clojure users.
Key features of λits include:
Dependencies: No third party dependencies.
Immutability: All datatypes in λits are immutable.
Pure Functions: Functions are pure by default. Functions with side effects have names ending in an exclamation mark (!), such as write! or rand!.
Type Mapping: All datatypes in λits map directly to JavaScript types.
Evaluation: λits does not support lazy evaluation.
Macros: Macros are not supported in λits.
Keyword Symbols: There are no keyword symbols. The notation :foo is simply shorthand for the string "foo".
Scoping: λits uses dynamic scoping, not lexical scoping.
For more information, visit the λits GitHub repository
Happy coding!

Collection

Description
Returns number of elements in coll.
Clojure docs
Arguments
coll collection | string | nil
Examples
> (count [1 2 3])

> (count [])
0
> (count (object :a 1))

> (count "")
0
> (count "Albert")

> (count nil)
0

not-found any

assoc
Collection
(assoc coll key value) → collection
(assoc coll key value & kvs) → collection
Description
Add or replace the value of element key to value in coll. Repeated for all key-value pairs in kvs.
If coll is an 'array', key must be number satisfying 0 <= key <= length.
Clojure docs
Arguments
coll collection
key string | number
value any
kvs Array<any>
Key-value pairs to associate.
Examples
> (assoc [1 2 3] 1 "Two")
[ 1, "Two", 3 ]
> (assoc [1 2 3] 3 "Four")
[ 1, 2, 3, "Four" ]
> (assoc {:a 1 :b 2} :a "One")
{ "a": "One", "b": 2 }
> (assoc {:a 1 :b 2} :c "Three")
{ "a": 1, "b": 2, "c": "Three" }
> (assoc :Albert 6 :a)
"Alberta"
assoc_in
Collection
(assoc_in coll keys value) → collection
Description
Associates a value in the nested collection coll, where keys is an array of keys and value is the new value.

If any levels do not exist, objects will be created - and the corresponding keys must be of type string.

Clojure docs
Arguments
coll collection
keys Array<number | string>
value any
Examples
> (assoc_in {} [:a :b :c] "Albert")
{ "a": { "b": { "c": "Albert" } } }
> (assoc_in [1 2 [1 2 3]] [2 1] "Albert")
[ 1, 2, [ 1, "Albert", 3 ] ]
> (assoc_in [1 2 {"name" "albert"}] [2 "name" 0] :A)
[ 1, 2, { "name": "Albert" } ]

update
Collection
(update coll fn) → collection
(update coll fn & fn-args) → collection
Description
Updates a value in the coll collection, where key is a key. fn is a function that will take the old value and any supplied fn-args and return the new value. If the key does not exist, nil is passed as the old value.
Clojure docs
Arguments
coll collection
key string | number
fn function
fn-args Array<any>
Examples
> (def x {:a 1 :b 2}) (update x :a inc)
{ "a": 2, "b": 2 }
> (def x {:a 1 :b 2}) (update x :c (fn [val] (if (nil? val) 0 (inc val))))
{ "a": 1, "b": 2, "c": 0 }
update_in
Collection
(update_in coll keys fn) → collection
(update_in coll keys fn & fn-args) → collection
Description
Updates a value in the coll collection, where keys is an array of keys and fn is a function that will take the old value and any supplied fn-args and return the new value. If any levels do not exist, objects will be created - and the corresponding keys must be of type string.
Clojure docs
Arguments
coll collection
keys array
fn function
fn-args Array<any>
Examples
> (update_in {:a [1 2 3]} [:a 1] (fn [val] (when (nil? val) 0)))
{ "a": [ 1, null, 3 ] }
> (update_in {:a {:foo :bar}} [:a :foo] (fn [val] (if (nil? val) "?" "!")))
{ "a": { "foo": "!" } }
> (update_in {:a {:foo :bar}} [:a :baz] (fn [val] (if (nil? val) "?" "!")))
{ "a": { "foo": "bar", "baz": "?" } }
> (update_in {:a [1 2 3]} [:a 1] * 10 10 10)
{ "a": [ 1, 2000, 3 ] }

nthnext

Description
If seq is an array, returns a new array with all but the first n elements from seq. If seq has less or equal than n elements, nil returned. For string seq returns all but the first n characters in seq. If length of string seq is less or equal than n, nil is returned.

null

null

null

Takes a function fn and a optional number arguments args to fn. It returns a function that takes the additional additional arguments. When called, the returned function calls (fn ...args ...additional_arguments).
Clojure docs
Arguments
fn function
args Array<any>
Examples
> (partial + 100)
<function >
> (def plusMany (partial + 100 1000)) (plusMany 1 10)
1111
> (def addHundred (partial + 100)) (addHundred 10)
110
comp
Functional
(comp & fns) → function
Description
Takes a variable number of functions and returns a function that is the composition of those.

The returned function takes a variable number of arguments, applies the rightmost function to the args, the next function (right-to-left) to the result, etc.

Clojure docs
Arguments
fns Array<function>
Examples
> (def negative-quotient (comp - /)) (negative-quotient 9 3)
-3
> ( #((apply comp first (repeat %2 rest)) %1) [1 2 3 4 5 6 7] 3)
LitsError: Expected non negative integer, got .
> (def x {"bar" {"foo" 42}}) ((comp "foo" "bar") x)
42

juxt
Functional
(juxt fn) → function
(juxt fn & fns) → function
Description
Takes one or many function and returns a function that is the juxtaposition of those functions.
The returned function takes a variable number of args, and returns a vector containing the result of applying each function to the args (left-to-right).
Clojure docs
Arguments
fn function
fns Array<function>
Examples
> ( (juxt + * min max) 3 4 6)
[ 13, 72, 3, 6 ]
> ( (juxt :a :b) {:a 1, :b 2, :c 3, :d 4})
[ 1, 2 ]
> (apply (juxt + * min max) (range 1 11))
[ 55, 3628800, 1, 10 ]

(!= x) → boolean

Description
Result is true if no two values are equal to each other, otherwise result is false. Note that only two argument version result is negation of = function, that is (!= a b) is same as (not (= a b)).

Examples

merge
Object
(merge & objs) → object
Description
Returns a new object created by merging together all arguments.

If two keys appears in more than one object the value from the last object is used.
If no arguments are provided nil is returned.

Clojure docs
Arguments
objs Array<object>
Examples
> (merge (object :x 10) (object :y 20))
{ "x": 10, "y": 20 }
> (merge (object :x 10) (object :x 15 :y 20))
{ "x": 15, "y": 20 }
merge-with
Object
(merge-with & objs fn) → object
Description
Returns a new object created by merging together all arguments. If two keys appears in more than one object fn is used to calculate the new value.

If no arguments are provided nil is returned.

Clojure docs
Arguments
objs Array<object>
fn function
Examples
> (merge-with (object :x 10) (object :y 20) +)
{ "x": 10, "y": 20 }
> (merge-with (object :x 10) (object :x 15 :y 20) +)
{ "x": 25, "y": 20 }
> (merge-with (object :x 10) (object :x 20) (object :x 30) (object :x 40) -)
{ "x": -80 }

match
Regular expression
(match r s) → Array<any>
Description
Matches s against regular expression r. If s is a string and matches the regular expression, a match-array is returned, otherwise nil is returned.
Arguments
r regexp
s string
Examples
> (match (regexp "^\s*(.*)$") " A string")
[ " A string", " A string" ]
> (match #"albert"i "My name is Albert")
[ "Albert" ]
> (match #"albert"i "My name is Ben")
null
> (match #"albert"i nil)
null
> (match #"albert"i 1)
null
> (match #"albert"i {})
null

#(expression)
Shorthand
Description
Shorthand for (fn [args] (expression)). %1, %2, %3, ... are shorthand for the first, second, third, ... argument.

You can reference the first argument using either %1 or %. However, please note that %1 and % are mutually exclusive and cannot be used simultaneously. E.g. #(* % %1) is not valid.

See also
fn
Examples
> #(+ %1 %2)
<function >
> #(* % %)
<function >
